        <ObservingDescription>ACTIVITY TITLE: NIRISS Astrometric Calibration (NIS-012)

DESCRIPTION: The distortion coefficients, pixel area map, and geometric scale factors of NIRISS will be measured with dithered observations of the calibrated LMC astrometric field located in the CVZ-South. This rich and uniform star field of approximately 600000 sources has been observed with HST ACS and WFC3 for the express purpose of doing such a calibration (Anderson 2016). The LMC astrometric catalog covers a uniform FOV of 5' Ã— 5' at an accuracy of 1 mas and contains about 218000 identifications of unblended PSFs. The observations in this program are well contained within this field and will meet the required accuracy of 5 mas or better stipulated by the DMS subsystem design requirements. 
    We choose to measure the distortion in all the NIRISS filters: F090W, F115W, F150W, F200W, F277W, F356W, F444W, F140M, F158M, F380M, F430M, and F480M. The filters span the entire wavelength range of NIRISS and include both single- and double-stack filters. The F090W, F115W, F150W, F200W, F140M, and F158M filters represent the six blocking filters of the WFSS mode and the F277W, F380M, F430M, and F480M filters, the four filters of the AMI mode. Exposures in NRM + F480M are also included to ascertain any change in the distortion introduced by the NRM. Seven of the reddest filters also match those in the equivalent NIRCam program (1069) and so will offer a cross-instrument calibration of the photometry for thousands of stars. 
    We also perform a consistency check of the distortion solution by mosaicking the field in a 4 X 4 pattern.  By placing the same stars in different parts of the detector, independent solutions of the geometric distortion can be derived. This approach will therefore insure that the distortion solution and its uncertainties are independent of the choice of stars selected for the calculations. An L-flat can also be derived from these exposures.
    The data from this program will offer important ancillary information on the on-orbit behavior of NIRISS such as photometric calibration, characterization of the PSF cores over the field, the L-flat, vignetting, image persistence, ghosts, stray light, and cross-talk using the brightest, saturated stars. This information will help refine several commissioning activities that follow.

ACTIVITY EXECUTION METHOD: OPE Commanding. Standard engineering proposal and commanding via the PPS and onboard scripts.

    In APT, this program is crafted with the External Calibration template. The observations are: Observation 1: imaging of the astrometric field in all the medium- and broad-band filters in a 4-point dither pattern; Observation 2: 4 X 4 mosaic of the field in F200W with an 80% overlap between the tiles for multiple independent measurements of the distortion. The large overlap insures that all the tiles of the NIRISS detector (2.2' X 2.2') are contained inside the square astrometric field (5' X 5') for any orientation.

PRE-REQUISITES AND DEPENDENCIES:
    1. NIRISS is at its best focus, e.g., program 1085 (NIS-010) has executed successfully.
    2. We require that all NIRISS commissioning activities be put on hold for 96 hours (4 days) after the observations of this program to allow time for the analysis and to update the reference files and SIAF.

REAL-TIME CONTACT REQUIRED? No

DURATION: APT returns a science time of about 2 hours and a charged time of 5.4 hours.

DATA REQUIREMENTS: The total data volume is about 5.5 GB.

ANALYSIS &amp; EXPECTED RESULTS: Simulations of the LMC field indicate that several thousand stars can be identified in a 5-group exposure. Star positions and fluxes will be measured in each exposure and compared with the reference frame to derive the distortion solution and the plate scale of NIRISS. The large number of stars and multiple deep samplings across the FOV will produce a highly accurate distortion map of the NIRISS FOV. The CRDS and SIAF will be updated with new distortion coefficients and pixel area map for all future science observations.

IS YOUR INSTRUMENT DRIVING TELESCOPE POINTING? Yes 

IS THIS ACTIVITY PREFERABLY DONE IN PARALLEL? No

COMMENTS:
    1. Filter-dependent versions of the geometric distortion can be delivered as reference files for the JWST calibration pipeline. The CRDS rmap will be set up to use the filter value from the science exposure as a selector for retrieval.</ObservingDescription>
